Now I have a complete picture of the codebase. Let me compose the full implementation plan.

---

## JWT Authentication Implementation Plan

### Architecture Overview

The implementation touches 5 files: 2 new files created from scratch (`src/middleware/auth.ts`, `src/routes/auth.ts`), and 3 existing files modified (`src/app.ts`, `src/routes/posts.ts`, `src/routes/comments.ts`). The order matters because `auth.ts` middleware must exist before the route files that import it.

---

### Step 1: Create `src/middleware/auth.ts`

This is the foundation everything else depends on. It must be created first.

**Key TypeScript concern — module augmentation:** Express's `Request` type does not have a `user` property by default. With `"module": "Node16"` and strict mode, TypeScript will error on `req.user` unless we augment the global `Express` namespace. This augmentation must live in the same file and use the `declare global` wrapper (required when inside a module — i.e., a file that has any top-level `import`).

**Key ES module concern:** With `"type": "module"` and `"module": "Node16"`, the default import syntax `import jwt from "jsonwebtoken"` works because `esModuleInterop: true` is set in tsconfig.

**Full file content:**

```typescript
import { Request, Response, NextFunction } from "express";
import jwt from "jsonwebtoken";

export const JWT_SECRET = "super-secret-key";

// Augment Express Request to include the decoded user payload
declare global {
  namespace Express {
    interface Request {
      user?: {
        userId: number;
        username: string;
      };
    }
  }
}

export function authenticate(req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction): void {
  const authHeader = req.headers.authorization;

  if (!authHeader || !authHeader.startsWith("Bearer ")) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Unauthorized" });
    return;
  }

  const token = authHeader.slice(7); // Remove "Bearer " prefix

  try {
    const decoded = jwt.verify(token, JWT_SECRET) as { userId: number; username: string };
    req.user = { userId: decoded.userId, username: decoded.username };
    next();
  } catch {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid token" });
  }
}
```

**TypeScript notes for this file:**
- `jwt.verify()` returns `string | JwtPayload`. We cast it with `as { userId: number; username: string }` after the try block assures it succeeded. The `catch` block uses no bound variable (the bare `catch {}` form) to satisfy strict mode since we don't need the error value.
- The `declare global { namespace Express { interface Request { ... } } }` pattern is required — not just `namespace Express { ... }` — because the file has imports and is therefore a module in TypeScript's type system. Without `declare global`, the augmentation would be scoped locally and not affect Express's global types.
- `(req, res, next): void` matches the signature pattern in `logger.ts`.

---

### Step 2: Create `src/routes/auth.ts`

Depends on: `src/middleware/auth.ts` (for `JWT_SECRET`), `src/db.ts` (for `users`, `nextId`), `src/types.ts` (for `User`).

**Logic details:**
- `POST /register`: Validate that `username`, `email`, and `password` are all present (400 if any missing). Check for duplicate `username` in the `users` array (409). Create user with `nextId(users)`. Sign JWT with `{ userId, username }` payload. Return 201 with `{ token, user }` where `user` omits `password` (destructure it out).
- `POST /login`: Find user by `username`. If not found, return 401. Compare `password` field directly (plaintext). If mismatch, return 401. Return 200 with `{ token }`.

**Full file content:**

```typescript
import { Router } from "express";
import jwt from "jsonwebtoken";
import { users, nextId } from "../db.js";
import { User } from "../types.js";
import { JWT_SECRET } from "../middleware/auth.js";

const router = Router();

// POST /auth/register
router.post("/register", (req, res): void => {
  const { username, email, password } = req.body;

  if (!username || !email || !password) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "username, email, and password are required" });
    return;
  }

  const existing = users.find((u) => u.username === username);
  if (existing) {
    res.status(409).json({ error: "Username already taken" });
    return;
  }

  const newUser: User = {
    id: nextId(users),
    username,
    email,
    password,
  };
  users.push(newUser);

  const token = jwt.sign(
    { userId: newUser.id, username: newUser.username },
    JWT_SECRET
  );

  // Omit password from response
  const { password: _password, ...userWithoutPassword } = newUser;

  res.status(201).json({ token, user: userWithoutPassword });
});

// POST /auth/login
router.post("/login", (req, res): void => {
  const { username, password } = req.body;

  const user = users.find((u) => u.username === username);
  if (!user || user.password !== password) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid credentials" });
    return;
  }

  const token = jwt.sign(
    { userId: user.id, username: user.username },
    JWT_SECRET
  );

  res.status(200).json({ token });
});

export { router as authRouter };
```

**TypeScript notes for this file:**
- `const { password: _password, ...userWithoutPassword } = newUser` — The rename to `_password` prevents the "declared but never read" TypeScript strict mode error. Alternatively `void _password` would suppress it but the rename is cleaner.
- `jwt.sign(payload, secret)` without an `expiresIn` option is intentional here — the tests do not check for token expiry, and adding it would not break anything, but omitting it keeps it simple and consistent with what the test expects.
- The `(req, res): void` return-type annotation on the arrow function matches the existing convention. Note this is placed on the function expression, not written as `Router.post<...>` generic — either works, but the inline annotation is consistent with `logger.ts`.

---

### Step 3: Modify `src/app.ts`

Add a single import and a single `app.use` call. Mount order matters: place `/auth` before `/posts` (conventional, though functionally irrelevant here since they don't share paths).

**Full file content:**

```typescript
import express from "express";
import { logger } from "./middleware/logger.js";
import { postsRouter } from "./routes/posts.js";
import { commentsRouter } from "./routes/comments.js";
import { authRouter } from "./routes/auth.js";

const app = express();

app.use(express.json());
app.use(logger);

// Routes
app.use("/auth", authRouter);
app.use("/posts", postsRouter);
app.use(commentsRouter);

// Health check
app.get("/health", (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: "ok" });
});

export { app };
```

**Only two lines change:** the `import { authRouter }` line and the `app.use("/auth", authRouter)` line. Everything else is preserved exactly as-is.

---

### Step 4: Modify `src/routes/posts.ts`

Three routes change. The GET routes are untouched.

- `POST /`: Add `authenticate` as first argument to `router.post`. Change `userId: userId || 1` to `userId: req.user!.userId`.
- `PUT /:id`: Add `authenticate`. After finding the post, add ownership check before the update logic.
- `DELETE /:id`: Add `authenticate`. After finding the post, add ownership check before the delete logic.

**Full file content:**

```typescript
import { Router } from "express";
import { posts, nextId } from "../db.js";
import { Post } from "../types.js";
import { authenticate } from "../middleware/auth.js";

const router = Router();

// GET /posts - list all posts
router.get("/", (req, res) => {
  res.json(posts);
});

// GET /posts/:id - get a single post
router.get("/:id", (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const post = posts.find((p) => p.id === id);
  if (!post) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  res.json(post);
});

// POST /posts - create a new post (requires auth)
router.post("/", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const { title, content } = req.body;
  if (!title || !content) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "title and content are required" });
    return;
  }
  const newPost: Post = {
    id: nextId(posts),
    title,
    content,
    userId: req.user!.userId,
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  };
  posts.push(newPost);
  res.status(201).json(newPost);
});

// PUT /posts/:id - update a post (requires auth + ownership)
router.put("/:id", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = posts.findIndex((p) => p.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  if (posts[index].userId !== req.user!.userId) {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" });
    return;
  }
  const { title, content } = req.body;
  if (title) posts[index].title = title;
  if (content) posts[index].content = content;
  res.json(posts[index]);
});

// DELETE /posts/:id - delete a post (requires auth + ownership)
router.delete("/:id", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = posts.findIndex((p) => p.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  if (posts[index].userId !== req.user!.userId) {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" });
    return;
  }
  const deleted = posts.splice(index, 1);
  res.json(deleted[0]);
});

export { router as postsRouter };
```

**TypeScript note:** `req.user!.userId` uses the non-null assertion operator. This is safe here because `authenticate` middleware is guaranteed to set `req.user` before the route handler runs — if it didn't, it would have already called `res.status(401)` and returned. TypeScript cannot infer this control-flow guarantee across middleware boundaries, so `!` is the correct tool. The alternative would be a runtime `if (!req.user)` guard, but that is redundant and would confuse readers.

---

### Step 5: Modify `src/routes/comments.ts`

Three routes change. The two GET routes are untouched.

- `POST /posts/:postId/comments`: Add `authenticate`. Change `userId: userId || 1` to `userId: req.user!.userId`. Remove `userId` from the destructured body fields.
- `PUT /comments/:id`: Add `authenticate`. Add ownership check after finding the comment.
- `DELETE /comments/:id`: Add `authenticate`. Add ownership check after finding the comment.

**Full file content:**

```typescript
import { Router } from "express";
import { comments, posts, nextId } from "../db.js";
import { Comment } from "../types.js";
import { authenticate } from "../middleware/auth.js";

const router = Router();

// GET /posts/:postId/comments - list all comments for a post
router.get("/posts/:postId/comments", (req, res) => {
  const postId = parseInt(req.params.postId, 10);
  const post = posts.find((p) => p.id === postId);
  if (!post) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  const postComments = comments.filter((c) => c.postId === postId);
  res.json(postComments);
});

// GET /comments/:id - get a single comment
router.get("/comments/:id", (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const comment = comments.find((c) => c.id === id);
  if (!comment) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Comment not found" });
    return;
  }
  res.json(comment);
});

// POST /posts/:postId/comments - create a comment (requires auth)
router.post("/posts/:postId/comments", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const postId = parseInt(req.params.postId, 10);
  const post = posts.find((p) => p.id === postId);
  if (!post) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  const { body } = req.body;
  if (!body) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "body is required" });
    return;
  }
  const newComment: Comment = {
    id: nextId(comments),
    postId,
    userId: req.user!.userId,
    body,
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  };
  comments.push(newComment);
  res.status(201).json(newComment);
});

// PUT /comments/:id - update a comment (requires auth + ownership)
router.put("/comments/:id", authenticate, (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = comments.findIndex((c) => c.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Comment not found" });
    return;
  }
  if (comments[index].userId !== req.user!.userId) {
    res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" });
    return;
  }
  const { body } = req.body;
  if (body) comments[index].body = body;
  res.json(comments[index]);
